At the end of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange swapped in the negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ equities accounted for almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed with its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilization plan, is also noticeable in our country.
Fall of shares in Asia
On Tuesday, Asian stock exchanges suffered a dramatic fall, even though the evidence succeeded in wiping out some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange's Hang Seng Index lost four per cent during trading, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the drop to almost 2.5 per cent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Chinese stock movement of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 per cent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Sydney Stock Exchange shares lost more than five per cent, but eventually losses were reduced to 4.3 per cent.
According to his index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 per cent.
"The hesitation about rescue action in the US will influence financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its own monetary policy, that is, independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should soon resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries might suffer the consequences.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the financial system support project, to which it should have spent up to $700 billion (almost 12 trillion Kč).
The legislators thus denied the call for the support of President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American actions were bloodshed and the main indices of actions had the greatest fall in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a fall of this magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gave way: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
American legislators made a decisive turning point in the talks on the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of $700 billion (approximately DKr 12 trillion) in financial assistance to the US financial system.
Success, however, is not certain.
Before the final version of the law can be published and put to the vote, the Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Says on Sunday to Reuters Barney Frank, the chairman of the Chamber's banking and financial regulation committee.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should be put to the vote in the Senate a priori.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor in reviving the financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market support can be effective, there will be a "disillusionment."
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form that the market stabilisation package should take, "said the Democrat Nancy Pelosi, Agency Bloomberg.
In her view, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met the US finance minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the government a final form.
It should repurchase from financial companies unmarketable real estate assets that cause financial firms to lose significantly and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we are, "says Paulson.
A signal for Asian exchanges
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to the Democratic Senator did escape Harry Reid, the legislators are making sure that the Congress will reach a final agreement by Sunday.
They want to calm down investors before the start of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress's decision could affect Monday's trade.
For the time being, however, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two chambers of the American Congress will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by any particular problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, there will still be a number of changes to the law.
The total amount earmarked for the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility to block the allocation of the remaining amount, following two steps: first, an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush welcomed progress in negotiations
Although the President can put his veto on this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put him in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed on Sunday to the vote of the law, and the Senate on Monday, "said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George Bush is himself pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesperson, Tony Fratto, said that Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
The Chairman of the Senate Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said that legislators have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the discount agreement, the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners, who have problems to pay for.
The government should negotiate further advance payments for mortgages it will buy back, while reducing debtors' monthly payments and allowing debtors to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that it is not known what the mechanism and price of buying back problematic assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government, "said Marek this week at the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree, as early as this week, that they support this plan and that they work on it as soon as possible.
This psychological meaning of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, is most important at the moment, "emphasized Marek.
An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear from this that it is better to buy only a phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a expensive gramophone for the house to put on the new album by Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disk, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are swollen vinyl discs in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're at least probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same applies to music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, just like a Pink Floyd fan would have trouble supporting earphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just reading music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the telephone.
Apart from the primary functions, telephone calls and text messages, he is able to read music and movies, to record them, he has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, to serve as a navigator.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no fridge knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing almost a miracle.
However, the universal nature of motive is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important energy gulfs.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for 10 to 12 hours, in most cases this figure is much lower.
In this respect, the music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are significantly better performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, moreover, you sometimes call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second charge for the work - this being valid even for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least efficient, after reloading.
Another problem arises when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all devices can be connected directly to the computer without a special software.
We can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without any reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need any software except iPod.
Simply fill the music device from the computer through the USB connector.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or the judgement of the user.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, you should be particularly interested in the life of the accumulator, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, basically, a background noise and if you will listen to it during the day, for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of doing so today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
All are able to read the MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have just this format.
It is one of the most widely used formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you have to do is visit the relevant operator's web pages (or those of another provider) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason for obtaining a musical motive.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is miserable and, in most cases, is limited to radio tubes made quickly.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether through GSM, internet or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always have their own motive.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you've forgotten your MP3 player at home.
It is also important if you still have headphones or handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in enclosures, which practically all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
In most cases, however, you will be limited by the absence of an exit for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best telephones and the best tools, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to control the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) generally have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support in principle only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get away even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you must not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, so that the ease of control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the furthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for long.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz on many occasions the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČT), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher for us than for the rest of the Union, confirmed this fact.
Thus, following the latest steps by the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper for some Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČT的), who has stated on several occasions that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, does chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with his own network is apparently no longer very lucky (indeed, now he would find frequencies only difficult).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which then conventional operators also had to react.
Yet even before parties like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those heard today in Britain were heard.
However, it became clear that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to earn more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
We should add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which has among other things the U: fon in Czech.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
For example, in the world, virtual operators are profiled as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by limited service offerings.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, relying on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesperson for Vodafone, questioned: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services. "
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promotional.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries of our area, "said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson of the financial group Penta.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were in any case not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The group GTS Novera, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not, for long enough, hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to make progress in the negotiations, "said Pavel Kaidl Group spokesperson.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the time being, its creation is accompanied by complete silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the time being, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us, "said Vlastimil Srše的of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project so far, which could serve as a basis."
She added: "It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now. "
Rather, Vodafone directs its attention to the completion of requests for its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said about this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the point of view of clients.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet. "
Responsible authorities: in tune with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
So what is the point of facilitating such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to understand themselves as thieves at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U: fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČT, when the U: fon was created, was exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is borne out by the information available to the public from the ČT's web pages.
Today, the U: fon is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "Competition in the mobile market has, moreover, recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands. "
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
It is not, however, just the attitude of ČT, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
In the face of this problem, however, the latter adopted its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of the potential interested parties has a priori not shown sufficient interest for the conventional operators, "explained in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of ÚOHS.
Such a statement would not surprise operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
All the more so as Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
Pressing for an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not in the interests of ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a matter of chance, naturally arises.
Similarly, a fuel price that is strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding liability for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecoms regulator, "said Chaloupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČT, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts suggest a different view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator logically has the monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
Even without accepting this argument, it should be at least worrying for ÚOHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
It is quite common in communications that the ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act has not succeeded in bringing about an expansion of the ČT's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
This is something that the ÚOHS representatives need to know very well, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work.
However, the operation of some sort of pseudo-virtual operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, firms dealing with multi-level marketing are mentioned.
For example, special mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected representatives.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company is in front of the operator figure of a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If this happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and which could lead to a cessation of cooperation with the company in question," answered our question on this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that any echo of such an activity has reached the mobile operators' heads.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
Auncun operator, however, does not object to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring significant benefits to them, and at the same time, as opposed to true virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, like ordinary customers of mobile operators. "
But this is precisely what should seem strange to ČT.
In addition, there is another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim that they have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable fall in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators were sometimes more, sometimes less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in developed countries took action, which defended not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies deal with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is disposed of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experience we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw the handle after the punch.
If the slide information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at home, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain immune to the rejection (discrimination) of others concerned.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mā j (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The singing is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose to interpret solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good saying, so that we could understand the words, which they sang simultaneously," he said.
Next year, the Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary.
In 1834, the song "Kde domov" was first heard on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), an original Czech piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously adapted it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
