The Prague public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip into its ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be inscribed in the history of Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Pragoese Agency of Transport) as the date on which the first passengers will climb in the metro, trams and buses, which, instead of having a paper ticket, will have in their pocket an electronic coupon.
At the moment, it is accessible to about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers may purchase a voucher 30 days or 90 days (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have it registered on their smart card in the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (the Transport Agency), located at the metro stations Muzeum, Mřstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letzany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility of buying coupons via the Internet on the web pages of the Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service this morning.
Those who start using the online store can permanently forget about the kiosks in the subway stations, where they had until now been impatiently trampled in long queues to get paper tickets.
In fact, they will buy their coupon via the internet and they will register it on their Opencard in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, there is at the disposal of passengers a desk with trained staff, who will help them with the purchase via the Internet and, moreover, record the coupon they have bought on their card," said the spokesperson for the project Martin Opatrný.
Besides libraries, it will also be possible to record electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compost the tickets and passengers may have noticed them already in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
Automate will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automates that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Simply introduce the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
That is, peri-urban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are used mainly by the inhabitants of the communes of Central Bohemia to access the capital.
