The Sudets were calling for a referendum in the United States.
In 1945, the Sudete Germans called for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This follows from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Sudete Germans were purportedly addressing the President of the United States with such a desire.
This follows, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov in the letter ask the US president not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation and want to be really sure that the words saying that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is dear."
Given that membership in Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only brutality, unscrupulous attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of one quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors."
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it is a good illustration of the expectations of the Sudete Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted that possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to obtain some form of autonomy for the Sudets.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as České Budějovice's German, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to visit him to teach them Czech.
"They thought that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš decrees, they would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way of characterising the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
The office of Minister Aleš Obebíček believes that it will discourage drivers from engaging in dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign, costing 150 million, will appear on television, radio, cinema, on the Internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and alcohol while driving.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the consciousness of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The sentence "You don't think" is written in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay."
Which must symbolize that one can pay for life a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" the spectators until 2010.
The Ministry has been inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where images with drastic images of the victims of accidents can be commonly seen.
It considers that this will lead to a decrease in the accident rate and in the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The Sugar and Whip Strategy against Drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time when they burn a red light.
Whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded of the drivers, "says Martin Kořán, the transportation psychologist at the Na Homolce hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertisements, according to the psychologist.
In his view, signs warning drivers of danger are already less effective.
"When a static sign warning against a hazard is installed, it will probably soon merge with the environment and drivers will no longer notice it," said Kořán.
