Nights of insomnia for shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
What a chance the politician used the word 'relatively' and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This one actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), alongside the DAX, gets a 1 billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect himself from market turbulence.
A person in confidence told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are issued up to EUR 35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, Depfa's daughter company bears the losses.
According to a newspaper article, the state financier had refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which has not been possible since then because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to EUR 2.37 million, and the own capital rate had also slightly decreased from 1.6 per cent to 1.45 per cent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions were zero compared to the same period the previous year, profits from the allocation of specified receivables and securities as well as the cancellation of provisions in credit transactions had dropped from more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only thanks to the large profits from the reimbursement of the downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as from the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern's companies, that the profit deficit of about 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had initially misspeculated about industrial real estate loans, which had then been filialized to the Aareal bank.
Because traditional state financing was not sufficiently profitable, Depfa had subsequently become more intensely involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of jointly financed projects between private and state investors (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, Hypo Real Estate must make depreciation which should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group's gains and losses, which is still rather vague.
The fact is, the dividends have been cut.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated to two-thirds.
The Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor since the acquisition of the Depfa.
It is stronger than other institutes dependent on refinancing in the inter-bank market as it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has again been considerably tarnished, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a part - about 50 Billion Euros - of the total Depfa credits of a short-term refinancing medium.
According to a statement from the Hypo Real Estate, the group's need for financing is covered with medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of working order at present.
Other sources say that refinancing would be carried out through the funds until the end of 2009.
The chairman of HRE Georg Funke's Executive Board explained, however, that Hypo Real Estate should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for Financial Services Supervision (Bafin) assume that Hypo Real's market capacity is now assured.
The bank's shareholders and creditors can only hope for it.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used to its full extent.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still at the door of insolvency on Sunday late in the evening, this temporary rescue will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are particularly good.
While the debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of second-hand loans are declining.
The most affected are mainly the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and those of course with a lifetime beyond 2009.
The bonds of the Hypo Real Estate bank seemed previously to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the same institute that brought the crisis into the institution by the acquisition of the Depfa bank.
As long as emission institutes, governments and less-affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed that the arrears will be reduced over time.
Or will happen what no one dares to hope at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the likelihood that safety was approaching has now become a simple and well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia primarily to long-term creditors on whether to separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can always use what they have drawn from to represent a carry-forward of losses for the coming years on the next capital income tax automatically levied on stock gains.
