Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge," contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove it so far, just as we cannot prove that other human beings have consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hard-to-reach terrain because Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he kills, escapes or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists infer from it a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience into that of animals.
One aspect is that circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the Prefrontal Side Cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least therefore for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from other primates.
Another significant feature may lie in the linguistic nature of man: much of his existence is related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, is neither measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses us great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily available scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies of short-term primate memory, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick have followed, one focuses more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal Cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what is the result then for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defence system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body) takes hold of living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially Man.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute them to others other than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the regions of the body sensation of the Cortex and the brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could be quite involved in any kind of transversal sensations.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict this, but I believe that this cannot be demonstrated.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in both men and rats is probably also perceived to be fear in both cases: how could it be verified whether rats and men feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviour is not enough to prove identical experiences.
Of course, nerve comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain trunks, but cockroaches don't even have a brain.
But is the brain stem at the origin of the sensations?
And even if we could prove this for man: how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have feelings.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since the human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behaviour than the emotional sensations of rats.
In all cases, there is progress on the nervous side, as the same is measured in rats and humans.
Since I don't explore the language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I don't know if they exist.
We could judge this as short-term, but I'd rather go ahead than hit a wall all the time.
I am indeed a pragmatic emotional.
