"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no stuffed clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where we discover at intimate gestures and stolen looks artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some plays with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the Flemish Photography Month program, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... by captivating the public.
In order to capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to make pictures on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars. "
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines," Bauer started a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plaque camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, remind classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises each day."
It is not about dancing or singing per se, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that we present these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book collecting the portraits exhibited in the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people," the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long time.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You're in front of people, characters you sometimes don't know, or who only give you a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true. "
This collection of portraits of the present flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people," is on display at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of the rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16.
