Recurrent drinkers will have to install the 'alcolock'
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver, who has had more than three administrative sanctions for blood alcohol, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting in a state of intoxication, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now reflected in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project lasting one year.
Its aim is to rehabilitate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety and also the Directorate General of Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Motor Vehicle Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a state of intoxication, take back the car.
Alcolock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than that allowed.
It costs more than €1,000 and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of infringements in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save 115 lives every year.
This applies only to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be carried out through ordinary channels, but reform through criminal channels requires reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote for an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in school buses as has been done in France.
