The first time this happens may surprise you, but actually it doesn't matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called sleepiness.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often linked to other sleep alterations such as nightmares, night terrors, night lurks (pee in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
Anyway, it's a little under-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or, on the contrary, with cries, cries, long speeches...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep alteration that can be cured (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as somniloquies appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because when he sleeps, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming of, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
It causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
