Interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
Most importantly, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In response to this tragedy and public grumbling, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster to happen again.
While Justice Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, just 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," says Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we regained public confidence, "she said proudly that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
From its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there was an outbreak in Europe of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has been holding the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result from it, namely Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures should be introduced.
In April 1999, people who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 were refused blood.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NAT), which allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests previously used were based.
TAN has shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This significantly reduced the risk that some donors would be infected without knowledge and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means distributing 12 million blood products before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission from a blood product occurs.
I believe we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, "said Héma-Québec's Chief Executive Officer.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant, "says Dr. Décary, noting that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
"Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need recharge with red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which represents on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
A healthy person, 18 years of age and older who meets the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, for example because they have AIDS or malaria, and if they have travelled to a malaria-ridden country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
As today's life is so unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving blood, "deplores Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth sample of cord blood, and we plan to collect more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing transplants early next year, "says Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
