Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both Houses of Congress.
It provides, inter alia, for better monitoring by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure to pay, and a right of scrutiny over the salaries paid to the managers of the enterprises rescued.
The U.S. Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," said the Democrat.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had been sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a further failure would have on investors' mood.
The deadline was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the US presidential election, who were late in the negotiations, were rather in favour of the agreement, although they did not fail to express their displeasure at the fact that they were forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has taken it upon himself to add certain provisions to the agreement, including the provision to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the provision on the salaries of executives of businesses that have been rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to be happy about.
But these measures are necessary, "he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outlines I have read [show] that this is something we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable, "he said.
The $700-billion plan is designed to buy back with taxpayers' money the dubious, risky and unbearable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
After 14 months of a crisis triggered by the break-up of a housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of sub-prime mortgages, then extended to other, more widespread forms of credit securities (ACAP) and led to a freezing of liquidity and the debilitation of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who had the first draft agreement over the last week.
It is believed that we have come out of this impasse since the democrats agreed that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty should only be insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for a first tranche of $250 billion, to which a further $100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
Another $350 billion should be approved by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will obtain equity interests in the rescued companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the turmoil has passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance payments to executives of affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote by the House of Representatives today, and by the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Voices continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
"Washington obviously does not hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that takes advantage of taxpayers. "
As host of a small group in Congress called the "Caucus of Skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presented things differently, but came to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us saying: Congress is being asked not to hurry and look carefully at the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
Following an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for €11.2 billion (US $16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas had announced that it had renounced to acquire its competitor in the midst of a shipwreck since it had lost 2 billion euros (US 2.9 billion) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, we get a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that times are coming uncertain. "
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on the verge of nationalizing another bank that had been malled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including over US $41 billion (US $75.5 billion) in real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and accounts receivable of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
