What could Zuschlag & amp; Compagnie do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly serious damage. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and the use of forgery.
According to the prosecutor's office, money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand into the funds of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other, into the pockets of some people.
Their method, which was also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect the money from the grants obtained by issuing bills of costs, behind which no actual services were provided and thus the associations never respected their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they purchased invoice books from the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies which were to appear on the invoices, it was decided, inter alia, during tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among others, with the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András, who, according to our information, was mainly involved in drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "tracking circuit," one of Lados's choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place provided for the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will later be named Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A boarding house, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
Invoice issuers with overwhelming imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. Neither Jobb Jövőért nor Hoppá's name appeared in their accounts, according to the information given to the prosecutor's office.
Győzā Farkas, the manager of the company, told the website hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond form, the fact that according to the bill, one hundred people had lodged there, did not stick either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have so much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time. "
Nor did the zealous invoice issuers inquire about Budapest travel agencies, which are part of their choice, but only organise trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on bills to be paid in cash, which also runs counter to the agency's accounting practices.
Moreover, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate for the four invoices issued in the name of Hotel Revfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services did not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. Moreover, the hotel employees only issue printed invoices, while the false were written by hand.
The investigation by the Public Prosecutor's Office reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes in referring to the carriage of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was investment advice.
Moreover, it is also for defects of forms, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont proved to be false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó sports course, both of which deny to be the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the forgers pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városert Egyesület was supposed to eat at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Invoices established deliberately
Another category of invoice issuers is those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Bâtiestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták consortium, has drawn up an invoice payable to the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, Collab Kft. manager was forced to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the foundation Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány, the association Atlasz Egyesület and the association Vörösfenyž Egyesület, for an amount of approximately five million HUF, but behind which no services were actually provided.
No financial transactions took place, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but organizations did not mention it in their accounts.
The next category of companies issuing invoices is companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the administrative delegate of the Managing Director of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the fuel and motor vehicle trade, whose head office was in Budapest, but where he could not be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. de Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov would also have sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the order of the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he secured their value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies functioned, which the accused explained by the fact that they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused as well as editor of the founding documents of the companies, he drew up invoices in their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave a total of 15 invoices to organizations, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor & apos; s office thought that 10 per cent of the money on the bills and VAT went into Kubatov & apos; s pocket.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to make fictitious invoices that were used in the Biztos Pont grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a grant to the public utility agency of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this grant for an amount of two times 500,000 HUF, but these amounts were not used for the objectives indicated in the application.
To prevent this from becoming known, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
In fact, these invoices were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office in the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will report on the method of making invoices, as they had previously done before the prosecution.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the least detail, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in its interest, or if so, the Socialists would have reached an agreement according to which in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the 50 million HUF, Zusi would bear the hat alone.
Today, he is probably offended, since applications for his house arrest, based on a reduction in his detention conditions, fall continuously into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of unrepairable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait at their own home for the end of the procedure. He does not have this possibility.
The Psychology of Overbidding: Why are we spending more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the commodity.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced from this type of competition, such as an eBay auction, and that's why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to establish a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the third-party surcharge, the whole under the brain stem, called striatum, moved intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of striatum.
In support of their theories, the economic members of this group of researchers continued to carry out financial surveillance analyses.
At the time, three groups overpriced a partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they thus made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, on top of that, they were to win the game, then they would receive an extra $15 as a reward.
While the third group received that $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is that the emphasis was on victory, while the emphasis was on failure.
By thus proving the neurologists hypothesis, the players' team members "against failure" were prepared for higher bets than those made by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation. "- found Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred thousand patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are being treated, because patients often do not know that they are carrying the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Liver inflammation and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against A and B viruses is recommended in any case. There is no C. Vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by general poor condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing may take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B. The disease is a disease that can cause death.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogenic gene destroys liver cells in a sneaky way. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
The contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, so the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at Oxford University realized an interesting experience in analyzing the level to which belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this bizarre experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshock, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a palpation technique of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment is carried out as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Hermine Lady painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was about its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics declared that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe," as someone "cared for," and they "calmed down, and peace invaded them."
When they saw the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% less pain than when they were watching Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided he finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases actually change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, it remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if we show believers a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would the sight of a better Virgin Mary produce better results?
