In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can provoke fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom, or possibly revolt against power that can provoke a counter-reaction among netizens.
However, it is confirmed that the terms sought are not only recorded, but in justified cases they are transmitted to a third party, and in such legal cases nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example in recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, during which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights netizens were able to sigh a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm-in-hand with EFF's electronic legal protection agency, proved its right to the court in front of the FBI. According to the ruling rendered in the future, Google will still not be obliged by any of the constitutional points to disclose information about the FBI's secret request of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But ultimately, it failed to obtain the lists of private users' searches, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the last two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is resisted by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and private domain suffer when they start using Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational corporations proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "wildlings" bringing together enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big companies, the "branched corporation," as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, catalogued as an invader of the world because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and the continuously refreshed package of programs has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, faced with the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that the geeks see very exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet, and what web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, draws precisely behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 does not concern anything other than collaboration, but the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind, and that we use the channels of communication at our disposal, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can hold a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then, he can link them to a tracking system, such as Friendly Feed or Blip.fm. These young people can also hold blogs, in which they automatically appear their most recent photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can see many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands in view of the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that dismissed one of his employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, we can be sure of one thing: the term of privacy is totally to be reconsidered today.
The one who lives an online life, is made up of what he shows of himself, and that is how we can define the principle behind the behaviour of today's young people.
The one wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to circumvent Google's monopoly, can do it (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using Google's search system, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them is not the least. Google's services online, through word processing to image processing, to reading information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not attached to huge server parks and which do not assemble our best profile, having existed to date.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords / AdSense advertising domains threaten the revenue of advertising agencies, while services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious headaches not only to Microsoft, but to many other computer program creators.
However, critical observers find, in addition to all this, contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the company's top management has refused, in its entirety, employee protests, after it has doubled the price of business kindergarten and after the company has found it too expensive to restore multiple daily, taken at any time. All this seems ridiculous apart from the fact that already in 2006, Google has acquiesced before the Chinese government and according to the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that hurt the good taste, as well as the interests of the Chinese regime.
According to one of the internal rules of the company, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is certain is that in the coming months and years they will move the world on new points. While some people think that Google's scan and archiving of books and magazines takes on such important dimensions that the company will soon find itself facing the Supreme Court of the United States, others are trembling in front of its health system, because in this one we can build a complete medical profit from our results from previous analyses, our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction writers. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian semitones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way just through Google's data.
