Intelligent Automobile Mimics Theft Theft
What method would be better for developing technologies to avoid an obstacle, other than the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of starting, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a self-driven, bio-inspired system, of the type BR23C, which he equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate aim being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval-shaped, which in reality looks much like our secure protective hull - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department.
The facet eye of the bee plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the facet eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is entirely instinctively carried out.
"If this were not the case, the mini robot car could not react fast enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotary motion, acceleration and slowing as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini robot auto
The BR23C uses polymer Lithium batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentrate, making their lifetime longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
You don't need memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
