The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue plan, designed to buy back the banks' questionable loans, and to use them several times, is ready.
In the first round, half of this money is going to be spent.
Reuters announces that during new debates extending until after midnight, Saturday, local time on the east coast, Congress leaders have agreed on the controversy that has existed for days and days around the $700 billion rescue plan.
"We have taken a serious step forward," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the American House of Representatives, who said that the only thing left to do is to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, commented on the outcome of the compromise that the program will work and will be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented. Pelosi says that this is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the economy's wheels in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8 p.m., Washington local time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., Central European local time), but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill responding to the name of the emergency economic stabilization law of the year 2008. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress achieved tonight, and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, White House spokesperson.
In addition, the program diverges from the Bush administration's initial proposal that the $700 billion should be spent on one-time buybacks of doubtful credit.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after the passage of the law by Congress, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Treasury Secretary to purchase bad debts from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The programme will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
The expenditure of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the Act, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase dubious debts, securities relating to dubious mortgages and other types of "toxic" debts.
Competent departmental officials have stated that buybacks can take place in the context of an auction, but also directly.
The rule allows the companies concerned to take part in an insurance programme, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that give rise to the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson stated that the legislation provides the necessary tools to devote $700 billion to the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the large buy-back of doubtful debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk that the system will lead to the collapse of one or the other major financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements, to be ready for the application of the law, as soon as it is signed" - he added.
On the other hand, bank managers in poor positions awaiting state aid can expect their severance payments, simply referred to as a golden parachute across the Atlantic, to be capped by the government.
Salary caps are mentioned only in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers assistance to the company.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys in an auction, they will levy an excess tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the repurchase of doubtful accounts, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to executives is not overstated.
For the image to be complete, it must be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The cap only concerns new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal ceilings will be in place on the appointments of directors general - commented the chairman of the committee responsible for financial services of the Chamber of Deputies, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the state acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan. In this way, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even win in the business as soon as the economy and with it the saved banks fall on their feet.
The bill mentions that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal that will rule on how the losses will be returned to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens mandated us, it doesn't protect taxpayers' dollars - said California Republican MP Darrell Issa.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes that it is the same people who are pressing for action, as those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial selling prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Domestic industrial selling prices rose only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry were only slightly up 0.1 per cent on July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, and then the production of footwear with a monthly increase of 2.5 per cent.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and apparatus (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry experienced an increase of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant share of domestic industrial production, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing prices showed the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price declines occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was in the profit-on-investment sectors.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those of the energy and material producing sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and processing sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-generating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
Industrial export sales prices in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
