Járóka said: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, hosted by France, began as a representative of the current presidency of the European Union.
In his message to the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokespersons of the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, as it is a violation of the law that affects most Roma children and thus one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened on the one hand by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and on the other by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of European legal protection and civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the Fidesz Popular Party group, Járóka warned that, in addition to the distinctions observed during the recruitment process, Roma people disappear from the labour market, primarily as a result of their low qualifications.
"An overwhelming majority of Roma young people do not have secondary school diplomas, and as a result of poor basic education, only a small party has the possibility of obtaining a higher education diploma."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in the promotion of other fundamental rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children means strengthening the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relations in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the more likely he or she increases his or her chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through taxes paid on his or her income and consumption, he or she participates in the State budget.
"Because of their European Union nationality, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education and protected from low quality and sectarian education." - stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the Member of the European Union, an objective-oriented and action-oriented collaboration is needed for an immediate acceleration of the process of desegregation of schools. To this end, compliance with the existing anti-discrimination directives and in preparation is of paramount importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment. We must give the opportunities provided by democracy to Roma children, so that they can participate as citizens of their own right in the future of Europe" - demanded Járóka.
On behalf of the European Year for Equal Opportunities for All, the objective of the Equal Opportunities Summit in Europe, which has been held every year since the summit in Berlin last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination at European and Member State level.
