Mp3 reader pointed to the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to full-volume music for an extended period using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which in a press release in Brussels cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, are at risk of permanent loss of auditory capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data - continues the person in charge U- this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also re-examine the existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies. "
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists-concluded the U- confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard which limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but there is increasing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
These data using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure can be well limited.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for extended periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
