Elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms to us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its moderate East Coast soul, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, that made itself felt despotically with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake preannounces or already leaves running: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been covered for some time, so much so that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the revival, the extraordinary revival, of the two sovereign-state category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with foreigners, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it is governed: that is, to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically, it is almost only here at home.
Political internationalisation really seems out of the question or has little to say: the obvious proof is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, shares between the various interests and between the various national strategies, fails to decide any common political line.
And so, it is the government of each state that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a allocation of funds: when you go through a difficult period, there is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the state-nation crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-greater importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at one stroke, that our future will have to settle more and more its accounts with rather little material things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but that are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, oil and water.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, provides for a fracture.
Which says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shade.
Moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership, underlies a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, in the collective mood changes of recent times, from the conservative ascent in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of Labour in Great Britain, to the rebellion of American Congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have ever more difficulty, which is not old today, in understanding and thus in representing the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and potentially agitates in a disproportionate way.
In view of all this, speaking of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is said well, keeping your eyes wide open, it is not without reason.
