Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Watch out for grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in the summer because they are desalterant and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption amplifying or decreasing, as the case may be, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if they are associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launches a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit juice, orange and apples is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, nullifying their beneficial effects and putting patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been strongly criticized for being responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-staminal and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
RISK MEDICINAL PRODUCTS - It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a two-year information bulletin, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this mix and to pay attention to drinking, if you take medicines such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT THAT PAMPLEMOUS- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit medicines.
Long is the list of active substances inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the department of pharmacology of the Public University of Milan: "These discoveries are generally, immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies which will have to change the information notes of the medicines if necessary.
It is always necessary to read the illustrative papers of the medicines you are taking, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist, "stressed the expert at the Ansa agency.
