Students who are victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market knows no crisis
According to the latest survey of the Sunia, the syndicate of tenants, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support - explains Sunia's head of the study office, Laura Marian- in these cities, the strong demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of widespread increase has begun even for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free-type contracts, unregistered, with no rent limit, sub-leases.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the tax review are needed to calm prices.
Looking at the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it ranges from a minimum of 650 euros (zone Bande Nere), to an average of 800 euros (zone Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (zone Vittoria)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350 / 400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250 / 280 euros for a double bed, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a double bed.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for a single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300 / 400 euros, for a single, you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei zones.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250 / 350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-Community students, have a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is 25 / 30% higher than that charged to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic halls.
The historic cinemas are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumption of single rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; moreover, it has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places full of memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a journey and so many emotions," observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix de la jurée de Cannes, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living cinema, lost may be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have mainly paid for them: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof which confirms that the first one responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is indeed the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multiroom cinemas: 195 screens in addition in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian farm has developed irrationally," says Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, not all of them are necessarily willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the missed deliberation of credit in favour of merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government is not complying with existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million per year.
We note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the mono-theatre cinemas of the historical centres and on the outskirts.
Among the normative measures planned are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," notes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna implementing other measures.
It is clear, however, that in order to counteract the superpower of multiplex, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradiso cinema" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, I turn on the other side not to see the panels blackened by dust.
