When energy is born from the waves, now the big ones start.
This is a huge deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface area and now the world's leading energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colosses like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now try to get their hands.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has now been studied for 100 years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil are giving a big boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by sea swell systems.
This quantity would be twice that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colosses to attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more of these companies have always been dedicated to traditional energy and rely on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies - said the spokesperson of a company associated with the American oil colossus, the economic daily Wall Street Newspaper - and she is assessing the possibilities of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question is concerned with obtaining a permit which the US Energy Commission will deliberate on, which is necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that just in Alaska, the Usa are still extracting oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. From New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, who travel the sea energy route, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Tecnology to be developed.
The experts talk about a technology still in its early stages, because marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
Large-scale energy production, however, requires the use of technologies with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through underwater cables.
At this time, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the contrary, is already producing energy for a commercial centre and parking lot using six underwater turbines from the East River of New York.
The movement of water during tides, rotates the blades of turbines, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electric Energy, deserves at this moment, the potential of tides.
Although this is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from the wind, the sun, or the waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others, are looking to the coast, have invested $7 and a half million in 2008 and are planning investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
